Let’s talk abs🌱

Copious amount of sit ups, dieting pills, endless cardio, waist trainers and all the other “quick fix” solutions offered in today’s society are not the magic solution to getting abs. 

Abs are made in the kitchen. When trying to transform your body often times people forget that diet and exercise go hand in hand.

So what are my tips to maximizing core strength and being able to see your abs? 

1) A well balanced diet
2) Resistance training
3) Get enough sleep
4) High protein diet 
5) Slight calorie deficit 
6) Drink plenty of water 
7) Stay away from high sugar drinks
8) STAY CONSISTENT. 

Do not forget the importance of the last tip. Nothing happens overnight. It takes consistency and patience. So just because you make a change and stick to it for a couple weeks doesn’t mean you’re going to see a drastic change. Quick solutions are usually temporary. Find what works for your body and stick to it. Enjoy the process and remember to celebrate the small victories along the way!

Happy Sunday🌱☀️🌷

Sacrifice for what you want or what you want becomes the sacrifice💪🏼

It’s been nearly 1 year of working to trim down and get to a physique I want to maintain. I’ve definitely made progress towards that! My peak bulk I was 158-159 pounds and this morning I hit a new low of 139..I am feeling healthier and happier at this weight so I am planning to maintain for a while as is❤️

It’s taken me about 10 month to get here! Of course there were times I hit plateaus and felt more frustrated than ever but I never gave up. Just over the past few months I’ve been intuitively eating which has allowed me more freedom to eat things I crave and not be so restrictive. For quite some time I was overly obsessive about exactly how much of what I ate everyday instead of taking the time to listen to my hunger cues.

Remember that results take time! Be kind to yourself. Slow and steady wins the race and whenever you’re at in your journey, DO NOT GIVE UP. I’m rooting for you and I’d love to help you achieve your goals.

HIIT workouts have had my heart lately! The best part is you can create your own so easily. This is how I like to design mine:

1. Choose 5-10 body weight or light weight exercises
2. If you want rests between each exercise make sure they are no more than 45 seconds long (we want to keep your HR up)
*Of you choose shorter tests between exercises then be sure to give yourself a longer (1-2min) rest between full rounds 
3. I like to do 45 seconds of work followed by 15 seconds of rest so that each exercise gets its own minute 
4. Workout your way through all the exercises using the same timing 
5. Complete as many rounds as you have time for or until you’re satisfied with the work you have put in
6. PUSH YOURSELF

To kick off this new year I am going to be real and raw..I ended 2023 not feeling super proud of the year I’d had. Last year I really lost sight of my priorities and neglected a lot of areas in my life. I stopped enjoying the gym and was in it less often, I started drinking more than I’d like, I stopped meal prepping, I lost my routine that I had worked so hard to build in Texas and really just started blaming outside circumstances for my own laziness. The truth is, everybody has shit going on and using it as an excuse in my case did more harm than good. This year I promise to be kinder to myself, prioritize my needs and stick to my routine (once I create a good one). I really want to accomplish all the goals I have set for myself this year. 2024 I hope you are a million times better than 2023. It sounds cliche but you only live once so let’s do this thing 2024👊🏼
